The English call the Monedula a Caddo, Chogh, or Ka; Germans eyn dol; and Saxons eyn alke. The Monedula is much smaller than the Pyrrhocorax, and nests in woods and hollow trees and towers of churches The third kind is thus described by Aristotle in the eighth book of his History of Animals 1-—
